{"/service/ndnp/idhi/batch_idhi_everglades_ver01/data/sn88056114/0041421194A/1907113001/0074.xml":{"full_text":"The Currency Problem.\nIf the eight} 7 odd million inhabitants of the United\nStates are not inextricably involved in bewilderment\nover the monetary situation it is because they have\nnot read all the utterances of the statesmen to\nwhom they look for advice.\nAfter a number of specifics had been suggested\nfor the cure of the ailment that is tantalizing the\ncountry, the Secretary of the Treasury hit upon an\nexpedient and put it in force in the confident be\nlief that it would restore the normal currency move\nHe authorized the issue of $50,000,000 in\nment.\ngovernment interest bearing bonds and $100,000,000\nin government interest bearing certificates, the latter\npractically the notes of the people to the people on\nwhich the people are to pay to themselves three cents\neach year on each dollar.\nThe President of the United States made haste to\napprove the action of his Secretary in a public letter\nin which he expressed a belief that the additional se\ncurities put forth would in some way relieve the\nstringency and impart greater activity to business\ntransactions.\nThe Secretary of the Treasury received like en\ncouragement from other high authority, which broke\nout in spots all over the country, sometimes with en\nthusiasm and at other time in the half hearted way\nof men floundering in the intricacies of a problem.\nFrom some important sources came unstinted criti\ncism of the administration plan and among those ar\nrayed in positive opposition to it is the chairman of\nthe House committee on banking and currency, Rep\nresentative Fowler, of New Jersey, a Republican.\nMr. Fowler declared that the crisis in the currency\npanic had passed two days before the President au\nthorized the public loan suggested by his financial\n'At this juncture, when the\nSecretary and said\nfinancial and currency situation was already well in\nhand, the administration intervened, against the\nopinion of the best judges of the situation.\"\nIt was the belief of this critic that the action of the\ntreasury department was ill-advised and that the is\nof additional securities would be dangerously\nsuance\ndisturbing, although he had faith to believe that the\nbankers of the country would be able to avert im\nminent serious consequences.\nMr. Fowler stated that the government already\nhad $240,000,000 in various securities largely on de\nposit in the banks of the country, on which it was\ntaking interest from the people in the form of tax\nTherefore,\" he said\nthis new interest bear\nation.\ning debt of the government should not have been in\ncurred, especially when such increase in debt is clear\nly in violation of the intent and purpose of the law,\nand is a violation of economic law for\nwhich the people must yet pay the penalty.\"\nNo stronger arraignment of the last financial act of\nthe government could have been made by an enemy\nof the administration, though Mr. Fowler is its par\ntisan friend and he prefaced his criticism with the\nstatement that the course to which he had commit\nted himself was personally and politically unpleasant\nto him.\nAnother member of the House committee on bank\nand Congressman Prince, Republican,\ning currency,\nof Illinois, calls attention to the fact that the gov\nernment has placed in the hands of the national banks\nof the country $240,000,000, on which it is drawing\ninterest and it now proposes to pay two and three\nper cent interest on another $150,000,000 for the re\nlease of money that will give to the banks from five\nno\nto six per cent.\nSaid Mr. Prince:\nretary of the Treasury is to all intents, in\npeace, adding to the interest bearing debt of the peo\nIt is not justifiable under existing\nThe Illinois Congressman was of the\n'The present policy of the Sec\ntimes of\npie $150,000,000.\nconditions.\" _\nopinion that the $50,00,000 needed to meet immediate\nof the Panama canal should be taken from\nexpenses\nthe idle $240,000,000 the government is generously\nadding to the business sinews of the private banking\ncorporations of the country.\nhave been taken from the\nThese expressions\nof Republicans identified with the financial\nmouths\nlegislation of the country and they were not prompt\ned by partisan bias, which might justly be charged\nagainst an array of Democratic opinion. Two other\nRepublicans of national importance, Senator War\nren, of Wyoming, and Representative Needham, of\nCalifornia, approve of the action of the treasury de\npartment and make public opinions in conflict with\nthose of the two members of the banking and cur\nrency committee.\nOther members of the national legislature are\nvariously quoted. For example, Senator Smoot, now\nfully accredited, pleads for a currency as elastic as\nthe matrimonial tendencies of his State\u2014something\nthat will adjust itself to the demands of the hour\nand the day\u2014and Senator Guggenheim, of the smelt\ning trust that manufactures the white metal, believes\nthe government should purchase silver liberally and\ncoin it into dollars.\nThus do the authorities differ and the people are\nalso at sea, though no more so than are the men to\nwhom they have entrusted the solution of difficult\nnational problems. Meanwhile such distinguished\nadvisers as President Roosevelt and Secretary Cor\ntclyou protest that if the people will cease hoarding\ntheir money and will pour it into the stream of daily\ntransactions, the stringency will disappear and panic\nwill flee before the return of prosperity.\nThe people themselves are well aware that they\ncould not hoard their money if they were so dis\nposed, for when they visit their banks with that in\ntention in mind they encounter only the cold stare of\nthe man behind the wicket and a printed promise to\npay them in the indefinite future. They know that\nthe panic is not a result of a loss of confidence, even\nthough high officials may make the charge, for con\nfidence has had no opportunity to exercise its strength\nor weakness.\nOut of all the discussion of- monetary conditions\nthat occupies the columns of the newspapers, the con\nscientious reader can gather no satisfactory solution\nof a problem that is interpreted in as many ways\nas there are interpreters.\nAgainst an Extra Session.\nIn the course of its recent proceedings at Black\nfoot, the Eastern Idaho Press club, presuming that\na plan was in process of incubation that would give\nthe Governor of the State an excuse for calling the\nIdaho legislature together in special session, placed\nitself on record in opposition to the suggested ses\nThe newspaper men of Eastern Idaho have,\nsion.\nof course, been attacked for their presumption by\nnewspapers and individuals connected with the brass\ncollar element, but the newspaper men do not seem\nto care.\nWhat they said at Blackfoot, under authority of\ntheir organization, was\nBy the members of the Eastern Idaho\nPress club, that we are unalterably opposed to the\ncalling of an extra session of the legislature for the\npurpose of passing a law postponing the date where\nby taxes become delinquent. We do not believe the\ncondition of affairs warrants anything of this na\nture. We know Idaho is in a prosperous condition,\nand we oppose any action having a tendency to create\na false impression.\nResolved:\nWhile the resolution does not so state, there was\nabroad a general suspicion that the Governor and\nhis advisers were seeking an excuse for convening\nthe legislature and that there was an ulterior pur\nbehind their not entirely concealed anxiety.\npose\nThey were not sacrificing any peace of mind over the\ncondition of the taxpayers of the State, knowing\nthem to be well able to meet their obligations in the\npresence of a strained financial situation.\nSome of the newspapers that have commented on\nthe action of the club and the cause of its action\nhave gone so far as to guess that the alleged hard\ntimes have been more disastrous in effect on the\nPinkerton detectives than on those well equipped\nresidents of the State whose taxes are about to fall\ndue.\nSo, if the Governor brings the legislature together,\nit will be placed under the eye of suspicion and\nwatched accordingly.\n<8* \u00ab\u00ee^\u00ee 4 \u2022S' \u00bb\u00ce 4 \u00bbi 4 4* *\u00ee* *\u00ee* *\u00ee* 4 4 4 4 4 I 4 *\u00ee 4 4* 4 4 \u2022i' *v 4 *i* 4* 4 4 *\u00ee* *\u00ee* 4 4 4*\n\u00bbI 4\n\nIdaho\n\n\n\n\n\n\nThe Great\n\n\nt\n\nTWIN FALLS!\n\n\n\n\nNORTH SIDE\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nt\n\n\n\n\nLand Opening\nMl\n\n\n\nv\n\nOccurred October 1st\n\n\n\n\n\n\u00ab\u00ee\u00bb\n75,000 Acres were Filed On\nin Three Days\n\n\n\n\n\n\n50,000 Tieres 1\n\n\n\nStill Open to Entry\ns\nt\nFollowing is what a recent buyer,\nwho attended the Opening October 1st\nand secured land after the Drawing,\nsays of the Project and the remaining\nunsold acres\n\"I have located on 160 acres of the land\n\nt\nt\n\nunder your canal system, and, though my num\nber came out among the last, and I thought\nmy chances were poor to secure a good loca-\ntion, I went with one of your drivers and\nmade my filing two days after the drawing\nwas over.\n\"There is plenty of fine land left and I\nwould not sell my location today for $5,000.00. <8*\nYour land is splendid, your climate all that\ncould be asked for, and your water supply\nunlimited.\n\"I am more than satisfied, and as soon as I\nam notified that the water is ready I am com-\ning here to make my home. Yours truly,\n(Signed) G. S. Freeburger,\nSouth Bend, Wash.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nt\n\n\nThe Gompany Sends People Out\n\u00abJ\u00bb\nOver the Land Free of Gharge\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nWrite for Circulars to the\n\n\n\nTwin Jails North Side Investment\nCompany, lad\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\u2666V v\nSole Agents for the disposal of all Water Rights\nand Town Lots.\n\n\n\n\n\nR. M. McGOLLUM, Secretary\nJEROME, IDAHO, via Shoshone 2\nCommissioner\n\u2022\u00ce 4\n\u25a0Si\n\n\n\n\nREED,\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nEACH SETTLER HIS OWN\nAGENT IN SELECTING LAND\n\n\ni\n\n.j, -j. 4 4 4\u00bb -\u00ce 4 4\u00bb 4* \u2022\u00ee 4","height":"19344","width":"14640"}}
